- "beacon lights in a vast ocean" refers to the top 5 detection events with the highest signal strength;
- "signal strength" is measured in dB and indicates the power of the detection signal;
- "event site" is a location where detection events occur, identified by its name and geographical coordinates.

- "significant number of fish detection events" refers to more than 10 events;
- "during the year 2020" refers to the date and time range from '2020-01-01' to '2021-01-01';
- "average duration of these events" is calculated in seconds.

- "fish detection events" refer to instances where a fish has been detected by an antenna;
- "antenna group name" and "antenna name" provide information about the specific detection equipment used;
- "CTH count" (Continuous Time History) indicates the number of continuous time history records for the event;
- "signal strength" is measured in dB and indicates the strength of the detection signal;
- "battery level" is measured in % and indicates the battery level of the antenna at the time of the event.

- 'Observation' refers to a type of event where fish are detected by an antenna;
- August 2020 is the period of interest for the observations;
- CTH count represents the number of Continuous Time History records for the event;
- Signal strength is measured in decibels (dB);
- Battery level is the percentage of battery remaining on the antenna.

- Detection events refer to instances where a fish is detected, typically through a tracking device;
- Water temperature can affect fish behavior and detection rates;
- The marking site is where the fish is initially tagged, and the release site is where it is released back into the wild.
